<script>var wp_meta_data = {\"authors\":[\"Katy Waldman\"],\"contentType\":\"article\",\"page_id\":\"100161207004\",\"keywords\":\"Books,slate book review,books,sbr1216,best of 2016,slate\",\"section\":\"Arts\",\"rubric\":\"Books\"};</script>\n\n    \n\n    \n\n      \n    \n      <script type=\"text/javascript\">\n        var teadsEnabled = true;\n        requirejs([\"jquery\",\"myslate\"], function($,myslate) {\n            if(myslate.isSlatePlusUser) {\n                teadsEnabled = false;\n            }\n        });\n        </script>\n    \n      \n        <script type=\"application/ld+json\">\n        {\"@context\":\"http://schema.org\",\"url\":\"http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/books/2016/12/best_books_of_2016_from_katy_waldman.html\",\"@type\":\"Article\",\"mainEntityOfPage\":\"True\",\"articleBody\":\"Slate\\u2019s Best Books of 2016 coverage: Monday: Laura Miller\\u2019s favorite books of the year. Tuesday: The best comics and the best book jackets of the year. Wednesday: Katy Waldman\\u2019s favorite books of the year. Thursday: Mark O\\u2019Connell\\u2019s favorite books of the year. Friday: The best audiobooks of the year. * * * All the Single Ladies by Rebecca Traister. Simon and Schuster. Read Slate\\u2019s review. Listen to the Audio Book Club discussion. Listen to Traister discuss the book. Traister was an indispensable voice during the 2016 election, writing about Hillary Clinton with warmth, lucidity, and insight. All three qualities are on display in her extraordinarily researched, cogently argued investigation into the rise of the single woman, which examines how unmarried women have long spearheaded social change and tracks the uneven line from past progressive movements to our current feminist flourishing. (I only wish she could have included a post-Trump addendum.) Especially notable is Traister\\u2019s attention to the full racial and economic spectrum of womanhood and to the oft-underrated bonds of female friendship. Heat and Light by Jennifer Haigh. Ecco. In this sensitive and sweeping novel, Haigh returns to the fictional Bakerton, a mining village overtaken by \\u201cfracking frenzy\\u201d in the late 2010s. The locals are divided over whether to lease their land to an unscrupulous energy company; transient drillers flood into the bars with their lusts and sorrows; activists descend; salesmen make bargains with the townsfolk, the devil, and themselves. By the end of the book\\u2019s 430 pages, Haigh\\u2019s patient, cumulative arguments (about greed, faith, chance, and community) have achieved real sonority, and we feel fully invested in her individual characters. Heat and Light is that rare \\u201cambitious social novel\\u201d whose interlocking pieces are as vividly and precisely realized as its panoramic themes. Modern Lovers by Emma Straub. Riverhead. Read Slate\\u2019s review. As she demonstrated with her witty The Vacationers, Straub has charm to spare. In Modern Lovers, an ensemble novel about more-or-less forlorn fortysomethings in twee Brooklyn, her trademark nimbleness serves a story of startling emotional depth. Straub\\u2019s adult characters (some of whom played together in a punk band) can\\u2019t quite relinquish the dream of youth; their children don\\u2019t know how to grow up, either. Disruptions small and large break across their interconnected paths, and there is deep satisfaction in watching an author as psychologically astute and empathetic as Straub play out their various responses. But the purest joys of the novel come from rooting for these relatably rudderless people as they attempt to sail into maturity with a modicum of grace. Moonglow by Michael Chabon. Harper. Read Slate\\u2019s review. Again, you may be shocked\\u2014shocked!\\u2014to learn that the latest novel from Pulitzer Prize\\u2013winning author Chabon, a shimmering \\u201cmemoir\\u201d about his grandparents, is among the year\\u2019s best. But the pleasure of surrendering to Chabon\\u2019s remarkable skills as a storyteller can\\u2019t be overstated. He excels on every level: his gorgeous, funny, looping sentences; his knack for the harlequin escapade; his deft swerves into emotional honesty and power; his intuitive mastery of suspense, tension, and release. Plus, American hero Ramon the cat deserves all the accolades for his third-act moment of bravery. Go Ramon! My Name Is Lucy Barton by Elizabeth Strout. Random House. In Strout\\u2019s deceptively quiet hands, a line of dialogue can seem simple or commonplace until it begins to burn, a glowing coal plucked from the furnace of some character\\u2019s psyche. My Name Is Lucy Barton is a masterpiece of slow-dawning meaning, an interrogation of family relationships that takes as its occasion an older woman\\u2019s visit to the bedside of her convalescent daughter. (And that\\u2019s all I\\u2019m going to say about the plot!) Night of the Animals by Bill Broun. Ecco. In the England of 2052, an authoritarian king lords over a broken, drug-addled society, while the internet plays directly on people\\u2019s corneas and suicide cultists seek salvation in the murder of animals. Homeless, nonagenarian addict Cuthbert believes he can save the world by releasing the creatures in the London Zoo, a task that plunges him deep into Celtic myth, the intrigues of the dystopian police state, and the scattered phantasms of his buried past. Broun\\u2019s \\u201cBrexit novel,\\u201d acquiring new resonance under the sign of Trump, is an eerie, wildly original debut\\u2014a blur of beauty and madness, like van Gogh\\u2019s Starry Night. The Nix by Nathan Hill. Knopf. Read Slate\\u2019s interview with Hill. This novel\\u2014about an academic malcontent; his accidentally revolutionary mother; and the constellation of students, family members, blowhard politicians, reactionary cops, video game addicts, ghosts, and Norwegian hobgoblins encircling them\\u2014is a Thanksgiving banquet of a book, a narrative table groaning with dishes both delicious and overdone. Hill, a gifted satirist whose lambasting of special-snowflake millennials and escapist gamer nerds can feel too broad, slips in tone from intelligent and realist to zanily experimental to lush and dreamy. His 600-page opus is an extravaganza of talent, a beautiful and idiosyncratic mess that for all its flashiness finds its most expressive voice when exploring basic human themes: love, anger, loneliness, regret. Underground Airlines by Ben Winters. Mulholland Books. Read Slate\\u2019s review. Listen to the Audio Book Club discussion. In Winters\\u2019 speculative portrait of present-day America, slavery persists in four states (the \\u201cHard Four\\u201d), and hypercompetent government agents track down fugitives with the amoral aplomb of James Bond. One such operative is Victor, a freed slave whose nightmarish past keeps erupting into his detective work. The book is profligate with its noir tropes, funny, gripping, imaginative, and inexorable as it gradually unmasks the unthinkable evil at its core. The storyline, in other words, doubles as a descent\\u2014and there is always further down to go. The Underground Railroad by Colson Whitehead. Doubleday. Read Slate\\u2019s review. Listen to the Audio Book Club discussion. Whitehead, who won this year\\u2019s National Book Award for fiction, isn\\u2019t hurting for laurels\\u2014and yet it\\u2019s hard to imagine drafting a list of 2016\\u2019s mightiest books without including this phantasmagorical slash into the dark gut of American racism.\u00a0 Cora, an escaped slave, travels through the South on a literal subterranean train, each stop an object lesson in a different ghoulish facet of white supremacy. Her resolve and dignity are moving\\u2014but it\\u2019s the author\\u2019s playfulness and unpredictability that elevate this traditional tale of hardship into something singular, fugitive, and strange. When Breath Becomes Air by Paul Kalanithi. Random House. Read Slate\\u2019s review. Listen to the Audio Book Club discussion. This memoir, from a literary-minded neurosurgeon who is diagnosed with terminal bone cancer in his 30s, is poetic and generous, intimate and profound. In clear and flowing prose, Kalanithi describes his self-formation as a doctor and then the evaporation of that identity as he becomes, again, a patient, starving for time. If some sections of the book are rougher or more abstract than others, the overall work recalls a world of almost pre-Christian luminousness, in which classical concepts like virtue, honor, and excellence still have purchase, chance or fate reigns supreme, and no person can evade the dark forever. --- Read the rest of the pieces in the Slate Book Review.\",\"headline\":\"Katy Waldman\\u2019s 10 Favorite Books of 2016\",\"datePublished\":\"2016-12-07T10:00:00-05:00\",\"author\":\"Katy Waldman\",\"image\":{\"@list\":[\"http://www.slate.com/content/dam/slate/articles/arts/books/2016/12/Waldman%202016/161206_BOOKS_waldman-2016.jpg.CROP.promo-mediumlarge.jpg\"]}}\n        </script>\n      \n\n    \n\n\n    <!-- BEGIN Krux Control Tag for \"Slate\" -->\n    <script class=\"kxct\" data-id=\"KGU_SbHX\" data-timing=\"async\" data-version=\"3.0\" type=\"text/javascript\">\n      window.Krux||((Krux=function(){Krux.q.push(arguments)}).q=[]);\n      (function(){\n        var k=document.createElement('script');k.type='text/javascript';k.async=true;\n        k.src=(location.protocol==='https:'?'https:':'http:')+'//cdn.krxd.net/controltag/KGU_SbHX.js';\n        var s=document.getElementsByTagName('script')[0];s.parentNode.insertBefore(k,s);\n      }());\n\n      \n      window.Krux||((Krux=function(){Krux.q.push(arguments);}).q=[]);\n      (function(){\n          function retrieve(n){\n            var m, k='kxslate_'+n;\n            if(window.localStorage){\n                return window.localStorage[k] || \"\";\n            }else if(navigator.cookieEnabled){\n                m = document.cookie.match(k+'=([^;]*)');\n                